While replacing a smoke detector with a new Nest Protect battery powered smoke detector I noticed that the holes in the mounting plate do not line up with the holes in the electrical box so I designed this adapter in Fusion 360. Holes 1 and 2 line up with the holes in the Nest mounting plate and holes 1 and 3 line up with the holes in the electrical box. This was designed for US electrical boxes with a distance of 3.28 inches (83.3mm) between holes. This might work for Canada and Mexico. I printed this in PETG, but you can use PLA or ABS. If it gets hot enough to deform then your house is probably almost burnt down anyway.

If your electrical box is metal the screws for holes 1 and 3 will need to be the appropriate machine screw, otherwise you can use one of the screws that came with the Nest.

Installation: Install a screw through hole 1 and into the electrical box. I temporarily put a screw into hole 3 to align the adapter. If you do this remove it now. Now install a screw through one of the holes in the mounting plate, through hole 3, and into the electrical box. Finally, install a screw through the mounting plate and into hole 2 of the adapter. Now continue the rest of the installation in the Nest instructions.

Although printing a Twisty puzzle core is relatively easy, regular home FDM printers do not produce parts strong enough. Printed pieces either crack on layers, or screws break their thread and pop out.

This time I decided to make the core by casting polyurethane in a silicone mold. Usually this technique is used to copy existing objects, but generally it is quite complicated - it requires a complex sequence of actions to get 2-part mold (there are plenty of videos on youtube describing this process)

In this thing I am printing a mold for a mold to simplify creation of a 2-part silicone mold. General idea is to cast silicone into printed mold, and then cast polyurethane into silicone.

Core size is 44mm

Printing and assembly algorithm

Part 1 - making a silicone mold:

  • Print Part 1 and Part 2 of the mold
  • Print 2 pcs of each wall type
  • Core is a hidden part, so no extensive post processing required. It is up to you whether to sand printed parts
  • Use 8 pcs of M3 6mm screws to assemble the mold
  • For one of the parts you should prepare channels to get polyurethane in and let air bubbles out of the mold. For this purposes I used short wooden sticks glued with a hot glue. Second half does not require this.
  • Put 15mm wooden sticks in 2 holes in the top - this is required to make a thread later (see picture)
  • Mix silicone and cast it into the mold
  • After silicone solidifies you can disassemble the mold and remove glued wooden sticks
  • Repeat for a second half

Part 2 - casting a polyurethane:

  • At this point you should get 2 halves of the second generation mold. They should be almost identical except for keys orientation and air/polyurethane channels in one of the halves.
  • It will be pretty hard to drill casted part and make thread there. Instead, it is much easier to make thread on this stage. Use 8 pieces of an M3 thread rod, each 15-20mm length, insert them into dedicated holes of the mold. For 4 of them I designed special chambers so you can use regular screws.
  • Fix 2 parts of the mold with rubber bands
  • Mix polyurethane and cast it into the mold via channels was made in one of the mold halves
  • After polyurethane solidifies you may get part out of the mold, unscrew thread rods and screws, and cut off material in channels.
  • Core is ready to use

Bottom line

Attaching also a regular 3D model for the core. There is one for whole core. Other is a half - print 2 and then glue together.

Remix of Sliding Storage Drawers by Intentional3D.

Longer, Slimer version made to be printed in multiple parts so as to:

  • Be able to print a bigger Storage drawer
  • Use multiple colors without use of a dual extruder setup
  • Better control Time and Quality of the print, It's no longer Hit or Miss

Exterior Size: 204x65x948 mm - 8.00x2.55x37.32 In

Difficult and/or time consuming supports are delivered in the .stl file (hexagonal pillars), you only need basic supports for the Sliders.

Need Acetone Soldering or any solid glue for assembly.

I designed this remix with the intent of making a longer, slimer version that could use my printing bed size to it's fullest.

The original craft was taller than wide due the the sliders, it mean your 1 part craft is going to be limited in Z size even though you could go wider in X-Y axis.

So i propose to make it into a multiple part craft. I even used the diagonals of my bed at 120% scaled size at a 35% Z angle. This setup is the biggest a Prusa I3 can go, using 24 out of the 25cm wide X Axis.

Other arguments to be made out of a multiple part crafts is that you can use multiple colors with a single extruder setup, and can better arrange your time. instead of a 36h craft that can miss even at the last 5%, you have smaller crafts with less supports, all printed flat on bed for an easier print.

Howerver keep in mind you'll need some simple Post-Printing soldering.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.20

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Important:

  • Use supports on the sliders to make the bridged rails.
  • All other parts do not use supports, they are included in the .stl when needed.
  • I suggest not using Loops and rafts, all crafts are printed flat on the printing bed anyway, save some bed place and make your craft bigger instead.

List of parts to be printed:

  • 2 x Slider
  • 2 x Upper side
  • 2 x Lower side
  • 1 x Bottom drawer
  • 1 x Middle drawer
  • 1 x Top drawer

Use diagonals if you want to make it the biggest possible, mine was made 121% scale for each files, at a 35° Z angle on a prusa I3 MK2S. It's slim, so it benefit a lot from those diagonals.

Other than than, simple craft except for the time it still require, about 10h for each drawer.
Yes you need longer to print this bigger version. About 50h total.

Important: Soldering

You need to fix the side parts after engaging the 2 sliders. Use the picture below as a model.

I used soldering with acetone. It solder very hard and is easy and quick.
Acetone is dangerous if it gets in the eyes or inhaled and is very inflammable.
We will use a very small quantity on top of a brush but do keep a leveled head.

You need acetone, a painting brush, tape, and preferably a cramp.

Solder the 2 side parts with the corresponding drawer.
I suggest protecting the areas that need to remain free of movement with tape.
You will need to remove the tape afterward.

Use a painting brush to put some acetone on the area that need soldering and NOWHERE ELSE.
Brush each part, preferably twice, after leaving the first layer for about 15s.
Present each the parts together and maintain them by hand for about 30s.
Once soldered, let it rest for 2h, preferably with clamp holding the parts, it will make them hold stronger.

title: Satellite
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
One day I was browsing the internet and doing some basic research on satellites and was intrigued by their design and the flawless manner in which they orbit our planet. Considering that there was no obvious way to obtain a satellite for myself I decided to make a model of a satellite of my own imagination that I can showcase.

The construction of the model makes use of both 3D printed parts as well as a combination of other materials such as plastics and metals. The decision to make use of other materials was based on the higher level of detail that I wished to obtain. However, the parts which were not 3D printed could easily be designed and printed if one wished to do so.

I hope this inspires many space lovers out there as it did me.

Notes:

Cooling was used as most of the parts that were printed were small in size and were thus prone to deformation as there was little time for the layers to cool before it moved on to the next.

Parts were sanded using sandpaper of varying grit to obtain the wanted level of smoothness.

The model was constructed using a piece of metal tube which formed the main body of the satellite. The top and bottom of the body were both 3D printed parts. The thin rods were made from pieces of aluminium rod. The frame supports of the rods at the bottom of the satellite were also 3D printed as was the cross at the top of the satellite and the tip of the solar panels. The solar panels were made from strips of plastic and decals were printed and stuck to the strips to create a realistic look.

The top assembly of the satellite was constructed from a piece of wood sanded into a hexagonal shape. A hexagonal frame was constructed by soldering together pieces of copper wire and was fixed to the wooden hexagon using strands of wire. miscellaneous parts were added to the wooden hexagon to create the look of instrumentation. Dishes were constructed from pieces of plastic spoons and the metallic wing-like structures were made from 1mm aluminium sheet bent at regular intervals.

The model was assembled using cyanoacrylate and to give the model the final look of a satellite ready for space orbit I air brushed the model a metallic silver. To display the completed model I constructed a stand from some scrap pieces of acrylic I had lying around.
I used Solidworks to create the 3D printed parts. The remaining parts were made from scrap materials and electronics I had lying around.

description.text:
This is a collection of more advanced parts I designed to work with the Hubelino Duplo-compatible marble run. All parts should work with the printed Duplo compatible marble run system as well. All parts include the OpenSCAD-Script I used to generate them and most are parametric so you can generate other sizes.

Some notes on the individual parts:

Slope

Put regular straight tracks between the top and bottom slope parts. A 4 nibble length of track drops 1 Lego height (half Duplo height), an 8 nibble length (long Hubelino straight track) drops 1 Duplo height.

Windmill

The size 1 rotor also fits pretty well on the size 2 base (and so on), especially with big marbles like the Hubelino plastic marbles.

Loop

These really need a lot of speed for the marble to clear them. Print a small one first and see if you can reach the necessary speed. I want to design some additional parts to make gaining speed easier.

Drop

The Hubelino marble should pass this hole if it has enough speed but drop down if it does not. Add before a loop if the marble clears it only sometimes. If it does not clear the loop, it can roll back and drop to another track below.

Other Hubelino extensions I designed:

Duplo Sound Block

title: 5S to 9v Voltage Reducer for FatShark Goggles

description.text:
This is a case designed to hold an XT60 connector and 24v to 9v voltage reducer. 9v works great with FatShark goggles without providing too much input power. I cut a 90 degree plug from an old router power cable and wired. I verified it fit into the FatShark goggles and cut it off as long as I could. I soldered it to the "out" side of the voltage reducer. I used 18 (or 20) AWG wire to connect the XT60 connector to the "in" side of the voltage reducer. The idea is to have a large sized battery in my pocket and have the wire run from my pocket, up through my shirt, out the neck hole, and finally to my goggles. When I'm not using my goggles, I'll pull the wire from the goggles and let it dangle. When I'm ready to fly again, I'll plug it back in.

These 3D pieces are designed to work with these components:

  1. 24v to 9v Reducer: https://www.banggood.com/DC-DC-9V-3A-Power-Supply-Module-Buck-Step-Down-Regulator-Module-24V-18V-12V-To-9V-Fixed-Output-p-1177908.html?p=6Z050013977120130325&utm_campaign=139771_1210911&utm_content=1081

  2. XT60 Connector: https://www.banggood.com/Wholesale-XT60-Male-Female-Bullet-Connectors-Plugs-For-RC-Battery-p-45394.html?p=6Z050013977120130325&utm_campaign=139771_1210911&utm_content=1081

  3. 20 AWG silicon wire: https://www.banggood.com/1M-8101214161820222426-AWG-Silicone-Wire-SR-Wire-p-921159.html?p=6Z050013977120130325&utm_campaign=139771_1210911&utm_content=1081

I printed this out of TPU, soldered the electronic pieces to each other, hot glued around the headset cord inside (to keep it from pulling on the solder pads), and finally hot glued the top and bottom side of the XT60 connector and pushed the top and bottom pieces together. Once the hot glue dried, I wrapped it in a piece of shrink wrap to help keep it together.

An optional "VaseBase" has also been included if you want the bottom of the vase to be the accenting color instead. Again, the scale of this part may need to be adjusted so that it fits the vase with your material and printer properties. This part is shown in the first picture.

remixed_from.title: X Motor mount for Anet A8

description.text:
HUGE CREDIT to Pheneeny's awesome AM8 rebuild mod, and Simhopp's great X motor and idler mounts which form the basis for this modification

I wanted to maximize the Z axis on my AM8 without having to buy longer extrusions, smooth rods, or really any hardware (you may need some more M5 screws and nuts of your choice for the extrusions) and I've always been bothered by the unused lengths of the rods and screws at top and bottom.

So I made a raised bottom mount for the smooth rods, raised top mount, and modified the X axis to put the lead screw nuts on bottom and have the shortest Z dimension possible. So now at the home position the Z screw nuts are only barely above the Z coupler, and at the top of the motion the X axis nearly touches the top rod holder. With these changes you can reach up to (depending on your X carriage) up to 310mm of Z build volume.

My carriage puts my nozzle right about 23mm below the bottom of the smooth rods so if yours is similar you should be able to get right about 310mm of Z, or less depending on how much more of a gap you have than I.

The X idler keeps Simhopp's original design for the X belt tensioner but should also be compatible with most other tensioners, see his original Thing for those files. The X motor piece has a mount on the back for a long M3 screw to serve as your Z endstop adjustment, and the endstop is on the left motor mount

The top Z rod holders are sturdy enough you can ram the top of the X carriage into them to synchronize your Z screws to each other if you like.

***THIS MOD IS NOT COMPATIBLE WITH CARRIAGES THAT HAVE STUFF HANGING OFF THE BACK**** such as bed probes, web cameras, etc. I am not responsible if you break something off by going above the top extrusion! Manually move everything first to make sure you don't have clearance issues, and you may have to reroute or extend your wiring, especially if yours doesn't already go OVER the top extrusion rather than under.

As near as I can tell this mod is just as if not more sturdy than the original AM8 design. At least in my fitting I had perfect spacing between the smooth rods at top and bottom so I don't have any issues with the axis binding

Please forgive the state of my wiring, now that this mod is complete it is all going to be redone!

Step1: Print the BudaShroud.dxf using inkscape or something similar onto ~225 to 280 gsm cardstock. The part should come out at 110mm plus a 5mm tab long and 20mm plus 10mm tabs high.
Step2: glue to create a cylinder, use a silicone based glue or something that will not burn in the case of getting too hot.
Step3: fold the tab oposite the join outwards
Step4: fold the two remaining tabs inwards.
Step5: unscrew hex screws from the wooden triangle on your budaschozzle.
Step6: place the shroud in position, and carefully punch a hole in the tab which is folded out to match the buda hex screw opposite the wires. Ensure that the shroud is not touching the heaterblock. (should be a couple of mm clearence)
Step7: screw the hex screw through the tab you just punched a hole in.
Step8: do the same for the two other inwards folded tabs, again ensure the shroud is not touching the heaterblock.
Step9: re-attach your budashnozzle and turn your fans up high without worrying about cooling down your budashnozzle!!!

This works on the property of magnets that when they are pushed together in a certain way, they will push away from each other.

To assemble, you will need:

  • Superglue (preferably the gel kind)
  • Some magnets (the file supports magnets about 18.80mm in diameter)
  • A metal (best strength; recommended for heavy duty use)

Steps:
1) Glue a single magnet to the wide flat end of the shaft adapter
2) Put the glued piece into the damper body with the magnet side facing up
3) Fit the metal shaft into the hole at the bottom of the damper body, making sure it fits snugly into the small end of the adapter, which should already be aligned
4) Push three or so magnets (stuck together) so that they repel the magnet inside stuck to the adapter
5) Screw on the cap to the top of the damper body

Notes:
To make the movement of the adapter smoother inside the damper body, sand the inside with sandpaper until it is as low friction as possible.

Note: This is pretty much just an experiment. At the time of writing this, I have not yet maiden'd this plane, though I will soon. It's got a roughly 1:1 thrust to weight ratio (with two 3S 850mAh batteries and an added 2 ounces to the nose for balance) and it balances, so it'll -probably- fly, but no guarantees. Dimensions are similar to the foam board FT Mini Mustang. The first version of this design was built directly from the foam board plans, but that came out ridiculously heavy. Version 2 here is completely my own design (apart from using some P-51D blueprints for reference), but obviously the design is inspired from the FT Mini Mustang.

All that said, if you just want something to fly and don't really care for the novelty of a 3D printed aircraft, just get the FT Mini Mustang speed build kit and call it a day. This will take more time and effort and offers few advantages.

This design has a lot of mistakes. It's the first plane I've ever built in a CAD program and is definitely the most complex thing I've ever built in CAD, and I learned a lot from doing it, but if I were to start over now I would've designed it better and spent less time on the design. However, since like I said this offers little advantage over its foamie sister design, I will likely not invest time into a version three - I'd rather design aircraft that would be more difficult to build with foam, and doesn't already have FT plans (some WW2 Japanese aircraft come to mind). I have uploaded the Fusion 360 save file if you wish to take a look.

This was designed with the FT Power Pack F in mind, but you could (and probably should) fit a beefier system in it. The fuselage is much more spacious than the FT Mini Mustang, and with the Power Pack F it needs added weight to the nose to balance anyway, so getting a bigger more powerful motor and a bigger battery instead just makes sense. With how heavy it is, the extra power would be put to good use. I will, however, maiden it with the Power Pack F as I consider that the "baseline" of power it should have.

Warning: I didn't take the time to orient each piece into its ideal printing position, sorry. It should be fairly obvious which way they're intended to be printed, though. Generally fuselage pieces are printed nose down, no support (use 15% infill for the Fore Fuselage piece, and 5% for all others); tail pieces are printed flat, 10% infill; wing pieces are printed with their leading edge on the build plate, using "touching buildplate" supports. After printing, remove the support scaffolding that is included in the design (the length-wise supports in the fuselage; leave the horizontal struts).

title: Amiga 4000 High Density Floppy Drive Face Plate and Button

description.text:
I bought an Amiga 4000 desktop last year which had a few nasty issues, including massive amounts of corrosion, broken traces, etc. In fact, the running count of parts I've replaced currently stands at 19 capacitors, 5 SIMM slots, one Ricoh real time clock chip, one battery, one F245 logic chip, and I just found a cracked solder joint on the Super Buster Rev 11 chip (This is as of March 2018...the list may get longer in the future). The -least- of my problems when I bought this A4000 was the missing floppy face plate and button on the high-density floppy drive.

I had mistakenly believed that I could swap in the face plate from a dead FG-357 floppy drive, which is PC-compatible and much easier to acquire. I found a nice looking one with dead electronics and ordered it for cheap. When it arrived, I immediately realized that the Amiga version of the high density drive (F-357 A) is about 50 percent taller than the FG-357. The Amiga high density version of the drive commands STUPIDLY high prices. I couldn't just buy a junk drive just for the face plate. So, that's how this project started.

This is not an exact match for the original, since I don't have an original face plate to work from. I know that the original had a rectangular light pipe for the indicator LED, but I opted to just have a hole instead. The hole engages with the LED perfectly, so it looks completely natural. The front proportions are roughly based on my FG-357 face plate. Note that this design doesn't include a spring-loaded front door. I didn't bother with this detail, since the parts required need to have pretty small plastic hinge pins, and making strong and reliable tiny pins with FDM is just not really viable.

Both the face plate and button are made to be a press fit. I did have to use an exacto knife to slightly trim the tab on the floppy button which fits into the eject bar on the floppy. I know from doing several prototypes that if the button tab is a bit loose, a drop of super glue will hold it in without damaging the drive.

I would suggest assembling it in the following order:

  1. Attach the button first. See the pic above to see how a properly-seated button looks.
  2. Hang a sacrificial floppy disk halfway out of the drive, to help align the face plate
  3. Slowly push the face plate into place, being careful to align the notch at the top of the drive with the notch on the top of the face plate. The long tabs on the sides of the face plate slide down to the screw mounts on either side of the drive. Since the screw mounts stick out a bit, you may need to use a screw driver to gently bend the tabs until they slide over the screw mounts. Once that is done, you should be able to push the face plate completely onto the drive.

Printing deets

Supports required obviously. Printed in nylon this should be pretty invincible in most crashes, ABS or PETG are the next best options. As long as you stay light, any of those three should survive crashes pretty well. Flex filament is not a great choice, imo, and definitely not recommended if you plan to top mount your battery.

If on a diet...

  • Mach24 with no modular bits comes out at around 6 grams in petg, not including standoffs or screws
  • Turtlefin weighs less than 1gram in petg
  • Battery Bays with Wedge weigh less than 6 grams in petg

title: i3 Plus Y-Axis Tensioner (Wanhao, Cocoon Create, Monoprice, Balco etc)

description.text:
Here's a Y axis tensioner I re-designed specifically for the i3 Plus and clones. It took a significant amount of texture out of my prints and got the walls looking much better.

I remixed AdamBath's design on Thingiverse (thing: 2368192) to use the M4 hardware that I had on hand.

Main differences with my design:

  • This one is 1 mm shorter
  • My version uses an M4 20 or 25mm screw and a standard M4 nut
  • Both belt loops on the same plane
  • Redesigned guide pin

There is 0.2 mm of clearance around the entire guide pin so depending on your printers capabilities, you may need to shave off some material from the pin to get a good fit.

Materials Required:

  • 1 M4 20 or 25 mm screw
  • 1 M4 standard nut (not nyloc)
  • 1 'Base' piece
  • 1 'Slider' piece
  • A few small zipties
  • Small piece of foam

I also installed this brace for the idler pulley a while ago and I would suggest using it to cope with the extra tension on the belt: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2561371

Notes:

NOTE FOR SUPPORTS: Only the 'Slider' part requires support to hold up the guide pin. If you use supports on the Base section you may not be able to remove them entirely from the guide pin slot or the screw hole.

Support settings I used...

  • Only touching build plate
  • 50 degrees
  • 30% support density

Assembly Guide
  1. If needed, trim material from the guide pin to ensure a snug but freely moving sliding action.
  2. Insert the M4 20 or 25mm screw into the 'Slider' part and the M4 nut into the 'Base' section
  3. Remove the M5 screws that secure the Y-axis belt to the build plate
  4. Loop the belt through the 'Base' section of the tensioner and secure the 'Base' with the same M5 screws.
  5. I added a piece of foam to pad out the extra distance between the tensioner and the plate it's screwed into.
  6. Loop the belt through the 'Slider' and place the guide pin into the base
  7. Tighten the screw to the desired tension
  8. Secure with zipties
  9. Trim excess belt to ensure clearance at the pulleys

This is a small test piece I made to use when playing about with support settings. I don't want to print a large item, only to find my supports are no good.
I originally printed out a part with counterbores & when I came to remove the support material, it was fused to the part.

This part is fairly compact 35 x 30 x 12 (Z) and printed in around an hour at 0.2mm layer height for me.
It has a standard clearance counterbore for an M6 cap head, a flat roof section (6mm from the bed), a 45 degree overhang & radiused curve with increasing overhang.
I decided that these are most of the scenarios I would likely encounter where support would be necessary.

Obviously, you will need to rotate this part in your slicer so the flat 'top' is the top piece of your print & the void features that require support will be against the print bed.

If you use this & find it useful, please upload a pic using 'I Made One' to show how your supports come out. Thanks.

description.text:
After our previous Keurig machine died, we replaced it with a new 2.0 version. My wife discovered that her large thermal tumblers would no long fit under the brew spout (even with the drip tray removed), as the new machine was shorter.

She purchased the Keurig base with the drawer to raise the machine up higher. This doesn't actually give you any more clearance, as Keurig's intention is that you still have the drip tray resting on this base. You can, however, position the brewer on the edge to gain more clearance. If you do this, though, you can't use the drip tray as it doesn't have any support underneath.

The solution was to design a riser for the drip tray that can rest against the side of the drawer base and support the drip tray. Now my shorter mugs are at the right brewing height, and she can just slide the drip tray with riser out of the way for her tall tumblers.

Note that if you're using something else to raise your brewer, this should still work - just scale the vertical Z axis (and ONLY the Z axis) appropriately. The model is currently set for a height of 98mm.

PLA should be fine for this, as it's unlikely you're getting very much hot coffee on it.

Y bearing holders for my Prusa i3 Bear Upgrade.

/!\ They are not compatible with original Prusa i3 MK2(s), MK2.5 or MK3!

 

Features

  • One STL file for each Prusa i3 Bear Upgrade version : Half, Full MK2(s)/MK2.5 and on Full MK3
  • Strong and solid bearing holders
  • Compatible with standard LM8UU bearing, Igus RJ4JP, Misumi and Motedis bearings
  • Bearing will be perfectly centered (including MK2(s) and MK2.5 where holes are not centered)
  • Clean shape to avoid any printing artifacts
  • Require a perfect alignment of the Y axis
  • Open source and parametric (STEP and Fusion 360 files)

 

Hardware needed

  • Half Upgrade : 6x M3x16mm
  • Full Upgrade (all versions) : 6x M3x20mm with 6x "normal" nuts and Loctite OR 6x M3x22mm with 6x locknuts. Screws can be longer, this is the minimum required.

 

Installation

Their is a mark on each bearing holders :

  • 1 dot -> Half Upgrade
  • 2 dots -> Full Upgrade MK2(s) and MK2.5
  • 3 dots -> Full Upgrade MK3

/!\ For Half/Full MK2(s) and MK2.5 only : you have to put the mark facing outside the printer: will face the Z motor mount on the two bearing side and PSU on the single bearing side. If the bearing holders are not in the correct direction, then the bearing will not be aligned on the Y carriage.

Do not tight them too much! Follow the same instructions as original Prusa i3 manual : http://manual.prusa3d.com/

description.text:
Pump connection portion of Belt Clip for a MiniMed 670G Insulin Pump.

Designed in two parts to allow more accurate printing without the need for a raft or supports.

Multiple versions of the other half of the belt clip are available elsewhere on Thingiverse.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.05mm

Infill:

Solid

Notes:

Designed in two parts to allow more accurate printing without the need for a raft or supports. I nested each part next to each other (not touching) to print them.

The through holes for the pin to hold the other half of the clip and spring are intentionally undersized. They should be drilled out to allow a pressed fit during final assembly

Assembly

After printing, I used a utility knife to remove the brim and clean up the edges. I cleaned the mating surfaces with an alcohol swab and used super glue to assembly them.

Care must be taken to line up both halves properly.

After holding them together for about 3 minutes, I set the clip aside and allowed it to cure for about 1 hour. After curing, I lightly sanded the edges and checked fit on the pump.

The through holes for the pin to hold the other half of the clip and spring are intentionally undersized. They should be drilled out to allow a pressed fit during final assembly

Modifications

I increased the length of the lever used to remove the clip from the pump. I found the original to be difficult to access, especially when a protective cover is on the pump.

In the future, I am considering the following modifications:

  1. Increase width of the tabs that hold the pin. This would increase strength and surface area holding the pin in place.
  2. Close one of the tabs so the pin can not pass all the way through. This would make disassembly difficult but, would help reduce the likelihood of the pin sliding out.

Introduction to 3D design for Fashion Classes

Students in fashion class with no or limited experience in 3D design and 3D printing will learn basic 3D design concepts using Tinkercad. The students will create a useable decorative sewing buttons. This introductory lesson, can be completed in approximately 90 minutes or two shorter class periods. The first class is an overview of history of sewing buttons and the introduction to using Tinkercad. The second class is student work time to create one or more buttons. This is collaborative project between the library media specialist and the fashion department.

Can you make a button?

Introduction:
Discuss the criteria for a sewing button, in particular size, decorative design, and holes (usually 2 to 4)

To clarify the definition of buttons and spark the creative process, explore the history of buttons and look at samples online or in person.

Step 1
Using Tinkercad displayed on a large screen, model for the students how to select a shape, manipulate size, create holes, attach and layer shapes. Have students replicate the same skills on their own computer screens to practice these skills.

Step 2 Shapes
Students utilize Tinkercad to combine shapes, indents, and holes to design one of more button. I always suggest that the students work in a large size first so they can see the details. Then resize when their design is complete.

Step 3 Holes
Students must create either 2 or 4 holes in their button large enough for thread and needle to pass through.

Step 3 Grouping your button pieces
After grouping their design, students resize the sewing button with a diameter that is between 15-35 mm and between 3-5 mm in thickness. Have students refer to a meter measure stick for reference when deciding on size.

Step 4 Share
Have students use the Share feature in Tinkercad, so you can access their file for later printing. I create a Google doc for students to place the shared link so I can access it whenever the printer is available.

ISTE Standard 4b
Students select and use digital tools to plan and manage a design process that considers design constraints and calculated risks.
